<h1>@HI{{yahari}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> <strong>@HI{{yahari}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{yahari}}</strong> is an adverb that indicates that an actual situation conforms to a standard based on
experience or common sense.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{beri-}}sanha<strong>yahari</strong>@KJ{{come}}masendeshita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      As expected, Mr. Bailey hasn't come, has he?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{o@KJ{{elder*brother}}sanha@KT{{tenisu}}ga@KJ{{above^hand}}desuga,
      @KJ{{younger*brother}}sanmo<strong>yappari</strong>@KJ{{above^hand}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The older brother is good at tennis, and the younger brother is good too.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{yappaari}}</strong> is a more emphatic version of <strong>@HI{{yahari}}</strong>.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{masaka}}, meaning "surely not" or "by no means", indicates that a situation is far from the speaker's expectations. As such
it is an antonym of <strong>@HI{{yahari}}</strong>.
</p>

